==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sol-fa
<hw>Sol`-fa"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sol-faed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sol-faing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[It. <ets>solfa</ets> the
gamut, from the syllables <ets>fa</ets>, <ets>sol</ets>.]</ety> <def>To
sing the notes of the gamut, ascending or descending; <as>as,
<ex>do</ex> or <ex>ut</ex>, <ex>re</ex>, <ex>mi</ex>, <ex>fa</ex>,
<ex>sol</ex>, <ex>la</ex>, <ex>si</ex>, <ex>do</ex>, or the same in
reverse order</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet can I neither <qex>solfe</qex> ne sing.</q> <rj><qau>Piers
Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sol-fa</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sol-fa
<hw>Sol`-fa"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To sing to
solmization syllables.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sol-fa</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sol-fa
<hw>Sol"-fa"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The gamut, or musical scale. See
